Theory:

An inventory system is used to manage and control the storage, movement, and availability of goods or 
materials in an organization. It helps businesses maintain sufficient stock levels while reducing shortages and excess inventory.

In this simulation, multiple workers (servers) process inventory demands from customers.
Customers arrive randomly and wait in a common queue if all workers are busy. 
The system also includes periodic restocking events.

The system mainly consists of:

Arrival rate
Service rate
Queue length
Waiting time
Number of workers/servers
COMMANDS:
GENERATE
Creates transactions or customers at specified time intervals.
QUEUE
Places customers in the waiting line.
ENTER
Allocates one available worker/server from storage.
DEPART
Removes customers from the queue once service begins.
ADVANCE
Simulates service or processing time.
LEAVE
Releases the worker/server after service completion.
TERMINATE
Removes the transaction from the system or stops the simulation.
STORAGE
Defines multiple identical servers/resources.
Scenario Overview:
Inventory Management System

The system contains:

Multiple workers (servers)
A single waiting queue
Periodic restocking process

Customers generate inventory requests randomly. If all workers are busy, incoming requests wait in the
queue until a worker becomes available.

This system behaves similarly to an M/M/C queue, where:

M indicates random arrivals
M indicates random service times
C indicates multiple servers
Key Components:
1. Customers

Customers generate inventory demands and enter the queue when workers are busy.

2. Workers (Servers)

Three workers process inventory requests simultaneously. Each worker handles one customer at a time.

3. Queue (Line)

A single common queue is maintained for waiting customers.

4. Restocking Process

Restocking transactions occur periodically to represent supply replenishment.

Conclusion:

The GPSS simulation represents a multiple-server inventory management system with 3 workers and a single queue.

